{:metadata {:description [{"text" "<p>Phosphatidylinositol transfer proteins (PITPs) are ubiquitous cytosolic proteins that catalyse the transfer of phosphatidylinositol (PI) between membranes [[cite:PUB00122281], [cite:PUB00155086], [cite:PUB00000922], [cite:PUB00039104]]. PITPs are an essential component of the polyphosphoinositide synthesis machinery and is hence required for proper signalling by epidermal growth factor and f-Met-Leu-Phe, as well as for exocytosis. The role of PITP in polyphosphoinositide synthesis may also explain its involvement in intracellular vesicular traffic [[cite:PUB00000922]]. Phosphatidylinositol transfer protein alpha and beta isoforms (PIPNA/B) are also able to catalyse the transfer of phosphatidylcholine (PC) between membranes [[cite:PUB00155085], [cite:PUB00039104], [cite:PUB00155086]]. PIPNB is required for COPI-mediated retrograde transport from the Golgi to the endoplasmic reticulum where phosphatidylinositol and phosphatidylcholine transfer activity is essential for this function [[cite:PUB00122266]].</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false}], :is-reviewed-llm false, :representative-structure {"accession" "1kcm", "name" "Crystal Structure of Mouse PITP Alpha Void of Bound Phospholipid at 2.0 Angstroms Resolution"}, :overlaps-with nil, :member-databases {"panther" {"PTHR10658" "PHOSPHATIDYLINOSITOL TRANSFER PROTEIN"}, "prints" {"PR00391" "PITRANSFER"}}, :is-updated-llm false, :name {"name" "Phosphatidylinositol transfer protein", "short" "PI_transfer"}, :wikipedia nil, :source-database "interpro", :type "family", :counters {"structures" 5, "domain_architectures" 0, "proteomes" 1480, "taxa" 5832, "subfamilies" 0, "interactions" 0, "matches" 15637, "sets" 0, "proteins" 14085, "structural_models" {"alphafold" 8050}, "pathways" 11}, :integrated nil, :cross-references {}, :set-info nil, :accession "IPR001666", :literature {"PUB00000922" {"URL" nil, "issue" "5", "authors" ["Liscovitch M" "Cantley LC."], "ISO_journal" "Cell